## 🧭 PROJECT CONTEXT

> **Most critical section. An AI that understands WHY this exists makes correct decisions autonomously.**

### Purpose
Unified firmware for ESP32-S3 that provides multiple independent modules (NFC cloning station, ultrasonic radar, web dashboard, CLI terminal) without needing to re-flash the microcontroller when switching between functions. All modules coexist and are selectable at runtime via menu or web.

### Goals
1. Modular runtime — add/use modules without re-flashing
2. Web-based remote control and monitoring
3. Real-time telemetry and historical data logging
4. NFC card cloning station (read + write MIFARE Classic 1K)
5. Ultrasonic distance radar with CLI control
6. DHT11 temperature and humidity sensor with CLI readout
6. LCD diagnostic display with rotating metrics
7. Over-the-air firmware updates (OTA)
8. Hybrid terminal (Telnet + WebSocket) for CLI access

### Non-goals
_AI: What is explicitly OUT of scope?_
- Mobile app (web UI is the remote interface)
- Cloud sync or remote access beyond LAN
- Multi-user support
- End-to-end encryption or TLS
- Support for NFC cards other than MIFARE Classic 1K
- Audio/video processing
- Real-time control loops (no hard real-time guarantees)

### Target users
_AI: Who uses this? Technical level? What do they expect?_
Ruben Blasco Armengod (personal project). Technical (embedded/hobbyist level). Expects a development sandbox where new hardware modules can be added and tested without rebuilding the entire system.

### Key constraints
| Constraint | Detail | Impact |
|-----------|--------|--------|
| MCU | ESP32-S3 N16R8 (16MB Flash, 8MB PSRAM, 240MHz dual-core) | Firmware size limit, RAM budget for WebSocket + CSV buffer |
| Fixed pinout | NeoPixel=GPIO48, NFC RST=21/SS=5, HC-SR04 TRIG=15/ECHO=16, I2C SDA=8/SCL=9, SPI MOSI=11/MISO=13/CLK=18, DHT11 DATA=GPIO4 | Hardware layout cannot change without rewiring |
| Display | LCD 16x2 I2C (addr 0x27) | Only 32 characters visible at once; 4-page rotating display |
| NFC | MFRC522 + MIFARE Classic 1K only | Cannot read/write other card types (NTAG, DESFire, etc.) |
| LED | 1x NeoPixel RGB | Single status indicator, limited to color/blink patterns |
| WiFi | Station mode, single SSID | No AP mode fallback; requires existing network |
| WebSocket | Max 2 simultaneous clients | Hard limit; 3rd client is silently ignored |
| CSV | Auto-deletes at 8MB | Historical data loss if not exported before threshold |
| Telnet | Single session only | New connection rejected while active session exists |

### Business / domain rules
_AI: Non-obvious rules that govern behavior. The kind that causes bugs when unknown._
- NFC cloning only works with "magic" (CUID/FUID) cards that accept block 0 writes. Standard MIFARE cards have block 0 locked at manufacturing.
- Menu auto-refreshes after 5 minutes of inactivity but only when clients are connected — saves LCD burn and CPU.
- CSV logging waits for NTP sync (checks year > 2000) — no valid timestamps before sync.
- Web log output is silenced for the first 30 seconds after WebSocket connects — prevents startup noise flood.
- Telnet accepts one client; any subsequent connection is rejected until the active session terminates.
- OTA is initialized but has no authentication password — anyone on the LAN can flash new firmware.
- Two FreeRTOS tasks run at identical priority (1) — no preemption guarantees; they cooperate via vTaskDelay(1).
- I2C bus is shared between LCD and potentially other devices; protected by `i2cMutex` semaphore.
- NeoPixel brightness is fixed at 50/255 (19.6%) — changing requires recompile.

### Assumptions
_AI: Things assumed true that, if wrong, would require rethinking the approach._
- WiFi network with SSID "NETLLAR_BLASCO" and password "978830522ro_" exists and is reachable.
- NFC cards presented are MIFARE Classic 1K with 4-byte UID.
- Target cards for cloning support block 0 writes (magic/CUID cards).
- I2C LCD is at address 0x27 with 16 columns and 2 rows.
- NTP servers (pool.ntp.org, time.nist.gov) are reachable from the LAN.
- ESP32-S3 has exactly 16MB Flash and 8MB PSRAM.
- Serial console operates at 115200 baud (USB CDC).
- Web browser is modern (supports ES6+, fetch, WebSocket, and Canvas).
- Device has stable USB or external 5V power.
- No other I2C devices share the bus at conflicting addresses.
- SPI bus is dedicated to MFRC522 (no other SPI devices).

